    "content": "Kannada Basics BookOpen Kannada is written with a rounded script. Start by recognizing vowels, then combine consonants and vowel marks. Read slowly at first. Accuracy matters more than speed while the script is still new. Script Shape Letter Sound Example Hint ಅ a short vowel ಆ aa long vowel ಕ ka consonant with vowel ಕಿ ki consonant plus vowel mark Reveal Practice Wrap the answer in answer. Add a template after to control what the learner sees. Use to place the blank anywhere inside the sentence; if you leave out the blank appears at the end automatically. Syntax Text formatters — bold , italic , ` code , highlight — work inside the template. Examples Answer only — blank at end, no template needed: नमस्ते means hello. Blank placed at the end — no required: The Kannada word ಕನ್ನಡ means Kannada Blank anywhere in the sentence: The Kannada word ಕನ್ನಡ means Kannada. Bold and highlight inside the template: आ is the ā vowel in Sanskrit. The vowel अ is a short vowel. Italic and inline code in the template: The mark ् is called the halant in Sanskrit. The syllable क reads as ka. The eye button always appears at the far right. The blank always expands to show the answer when clicked, regardless of where in the sentence it sits. Callout Examples Use callouts to mark learning hints, pronunciation reminders, and practice warnings. Write a simple note like this: Read each new word aloud before writing it. Add a custom title when the callout needs a clearer label: [Pronunciation Tip] Say the vowel slowly, then attach it to the consonant. Use caution for mistakes learners should notice early: [Common Mix up] Do not treat long and short vowel sounds as the same sound. Use info for helpful context: [Study Habit] A small daily reading habit is better than one long weekly session. Use danger sparingly for a serious warning: [Avoid This] Do not memorize random word lists without reading them in sentences. Learning Flow Here is a richer Mermaid example for planning a study loop: Markdown Features Lexora articles support familiar markdown plus a few learning focused helpers. Use Lucide icons inline with IconName. Great for practice Sparkles and review BookOpen. Find more icon names at [lucide.dev/icons](https://lucide.dev/icons). Use the PascalCase name shown by Lucide, such as BookOpen, Languages, Brain, Volume2, or House. Use tables for compact vocabulary: Kannada Transliteration Meaning ನೀರು neeru water ಮನೆ mane house Use code fences for examples, including Mermaid diagrams: mermaid flowchart LR word[Word] meaning[Meaning] Use reveal blanks for practice: Use emoji labels for image assisted reading. You can use built in names like house, water, and book, or paste any emoji directly inside the brackets. Sizes are normal, medium, big, and huge. Add meaningTamil only when an extra Tamil meaning is useful. house ಮನೆ mane home வீடு water ನೀರು neeru water book ಪುಸ್ತಕ pustaka book 🌳 ಮರ mara tree For more emoji, use your OS emoji picker or a Unicode emoji list such as [unicode.org/emoji/charts/full emoji list.html](https://unicode.org/emoji/charts/full emoji list.html), then paste the emoji directly into 😀. Use textWord when a word does not need an image. Add meaningTamil only when a rare extra Tamil meaning helps. ಮನೆ mane home வீடு ನೀರು neeru water Use sentence when a full sentence needs transliteration, meaning, or a rare Tamil meaning. Mark important words with highlight. ಅವಳು ಮನೆಗೆ ಹೋಗುತ್ತಾಳೆ avalu manege hoguttale She goes home. அவள் வீட்டிற்கு செல்கிறாள். ಮಕ್ಕಳು ಶಾಲೆಯಲ್ಲಿ ಪುಸ್ತಕಗಳನ್ನು ಓದುತ್ತಾರೆ makkalu shaleyalli pustakagalannu oduttare The children read books at school. Character Conversations Character conversations are useful for short teaching moments. Consecutive messages alternate sides automatically. Write it like this: Try reading the word slowly before guessing the meaning. So I should notice the sound first, then the word? You can force a side with align=\"right\" or align=\"left\". {align=\"right\"} Keep this reminder near the practice question.",
